# gen190 (basic-chat cat.4): arithmetic in natural language. The four operations
# asked in many surface forms all reduce to the same oracle — these frames are
# structural extractors of (operator, operands), not stored phrases, so they
# generalize over operands and number words.

# Operator WORDS that take two words ("divided by") and bare infix.
> what is 100 divided by 4
< 25.
> six times seven
< 42.
> six by seven
< 42.

# Number-WORD operands compute (parse_value), no "what is" needed.
> what is two plus two
< 4.

# Verb-led imperative frames.
> add 5 and 7
< 12.
> subtract 3 from 10
< 7.
> multiply 4 by 9
< 36.
> divide 20 by 5
< 4.

# Unary "of"-frames and suffixes over a single operand.
> what is half of 50
< 25.
> what is double of 8
< 16.
> what is the square root of 16
< 4.
> what is 3 squared
< 9.
> what is 5 factorial
< 120.

# Percent and n-ary list frames.
> what is 20 percent of 100
< 20.
> what is the sum of 3 and 4 and 5
< 12.
> what is the average of 2 and 4 and 6
< 4.

# Number-property predicates.
> is 15 a prime number
< No, 15 is not a prime number.
> is 8 an even number
< Yes, 8 is an even number.

# Chained infix folds left to right.
> how much is 1+1+1+1+1
< 5.

# Anti-overreach: a process loop that merely MENTIONS "double"/"even" (>=2
# numbers) is left for mod_agent, not claimed as a one-shot computation.
> start at 3 and double until you reach 50
< Reached 96 after 5 steps: 3 -> 6 -> 12 -> 24 -> 48 -> 96.
